\begin{abstract}
In this paper we model the emission from a relativistically expanding
$e^+e^-$ pair plasma fireball originating near the surface of a heated
neutron star.  This pair fireball is deposited via the annihilation of
neutrino pairs emanating from the surface of the hot neutron star.
The heating of neutron stars may occur in close neutron star binary
systems near their last stable orbit.  We model the relativistic
expansion and subsequent emission of the plasma and find $\sim 10^{51}
- 10^{52}$ ergs in $\gamma$-rays are produced with spectral and
temporal properties consistent with observed gamma-ray bursts.
\end{abstract}

